    <!-- Page Content -->
    <div class="container">

        <!-- Introduction Row -->
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h1 class="page-header">What is Color Blindess?
                    <small>The Important Facts</small>
                </h1>
                <p>Color blindess is a disorder that alters the ways people perceive color. The people with this disorder are either unable to differentiate different colors or be unable to see a certain shade completely. Contrary to what many people believe, color blindness doesn't always mean that a person is completely unable to see colors. The disorder affects certain cells in our eyes which are shaped like cones and help us perceive the colors of light which are green, blue, and red.There are many types of color blindess, each type having to do with what cone is missing.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h1 class="page-header">Who is affected by the disorder?
                    <small>The Statistics</small>
                </h1>
                <p>Colorblindess is a disorder which is linked to the X-chromosome. This means that if a mother is a carrier for the disorder, there is a 50% chance the son will have it. Due to this property, many men suffer from colorblindess than women do. Keep in mind, however, that contrary to what many people think, women are still susceptible to having the disorder. Colorblindess is found mostly in Caucasians at a frequency of 8% of the male population and 0.5% of the female population.<p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <!-- Team Members Row -->
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h2 class="page-header">Could you be affected?
                <small>Look at the following pictures to find out if you have a form of the disorder.</small></h2>
                
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4 col-sm-6 text-center">
                <img class="img-circle img-responsive img-center" src="http://www.colour-blindness.com/CBTests/ishihara/Plate1.gif" alt="">
                <h3>Do you see a 12?
                </h3>
                <p>This slide is designed so that everybody can see the number.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4 col-sm-6 text-center">
                <img class="img-circle img-responsive img-center" src="http://www.colour-blindness.com/CBTests/ishihara/Plate2.gif" alt="">
                <h3>Do you see the 8?
                </h3>
                <p>People with normal vision are able to see the 8. If you see a 3 then you have a form of red-green colorblindess.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4 col-sm-6 text-center">
                <img class="img-circle img-responsive img-center" src="http://www.colour-blindness.com/CBTests/ishihara/Plate3.gif" alt="">
                <h3>Do you see the 29?
                </h3>
                <p>People with normal vision see the 29. If you see a 70, you have a form of red-green colorblindness.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4 col-sm-6 text-center">
                <img class="img-circle img-responsive img-center" src="http://www.colour-blindness.com/CBTests/ishihara/Plate4.gif" alt="">
                <h3>Do you see the 5?
                </h3>
                <p>If you have normal vision, you see a 5. If you have red-green colorblindess you would see a 2.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4 col-sm-6 text-center">
                <img class="img-circle img-responsive img-center" src="http://www.colour-blindness.com/CBTests/ishihara/Plate8.gif" alt="">
